I’ve been having a lot of conversations in real life about how estranged people are feeling from the Christian Conservative moniker. That they’re beginning to feel the same way about conservatives as they long have liberals. The beliefs seem to be getting harder to line up with Scripture. Anger seems to touch everything they do and say. They’re more known for what they’re against than what they’re for. Less accepting, more divided, and on and on it goes.

And I don’t know if it’s me & the people who feel like me who are moving. I think the same thing that happened to liberals when they swung too hard is happening to conservatives. One side believes men can be women and the other that Trump is the second coming of Christ. One side believes they can do whatever they want without consequence, and the other thinks everything is evil and sinful. It’s enough to give you whiplash.

It can be exhausting to take heat from both sides of the proverbial aisle. Too conservative for progressives and somehow at the same time too progressive for conservatives. Ripped up one side for your theological beliefs and down the other for your politics. I wonder if it stems from our human obsession with labeling things and then huddling into tribes that adhere to those labels. We’ve been doing it since the beginning of time, why would we stop now?

I don’t have a bow to wrap this up in, I just wanted those who feel the same to know they’re not alone and aren’t the only ones wrestling. Maybe being politically homeless is ideal considering we’re not of this world. I don’t know what the answer is, but I’m willing to keep searching for it, taking the heat that comes with the territory, and being willing to be wrong.

Christian Icks

So when I first saw this story on Twitter I rolled my eyes at the outraged reaction a lot of conservatives were having.

My take was “why can’t it just be cool that a woman now stands with Moses & Confucius? I don’t necessarily like the style, but there’s a lot of art I don’t like.”

After reading the statements made by the artist about her creative inspiration it was more like “really guys? A gold statue in honor of abortion? You could at least act like you’re not copying Exodus 32.”

I get it. The issue of pro-life / pro-choice is important to us. It divides us. But for the love — why is our sole representation in media and culture today about our reproductive abilities?

What happened to “I am woman, hear me roar”? What happened to being so much more than a sex object?

I know the response will be “I don’t have the right to my own body anymore, there’s nothing else worth talking about!” But yes you do. By & large, excluding ~1% of cases, you do have rights over you body. You do.

I know this is important to us, but if women are going to be represented in statue form, could it have been about one of the other millions of ways women have shaped history?

There’s a typo. I’m okay with it.

I know the shadow bitterness and discontent cast on your life and I’m sure they’ll pass over mine again. But for now, I’ll bask in the sun whether it’s in a hill or a valley.

Amidst one of the craziest weeks the country has seen in a minute (which is saying something, honestly), revival is breaking out. A college chapel service is going on its seventh day running and across the nation others join them. Millions are following along on social media, an often destructive force suddenly leveraged for God’s kingdom on a massive level. 

The people span different generations, races, socioeconomic statuses, and I would guess secondary theological issues, and they don’t care. They’re there to worship the God they all love and serve. I like to imagine Satan throwing a temper tantrum, flipping trains and sending balloons in an attempt to distract us from the Jesus-fueled-wildfire breaking out (this is an illustration, not a theological belief or statement.)

And still, Christians grumble. They call it manipulation, question motives. What I’m sure began as a righteous pursuit of “testing the spirits” has degenerated into a spirit of criticism. 

We’ve lost our wonder.

We’ve carefully dissected the stories in Scripture to make them more digestible, explainable, and comfortable. We tuck away the supernatural, the things we can’t define. We forget that disciples have been performing miracles and proselytizing and casting out demons for almost two thousand years.

We have to stop sanitizing Scripture. We have to take back the wonder the early church had. Let revival run rampant. Trust the Holy Spirit with the rest. Maybe what’s happening at Asbury isn’t God ordained. But He’s using it anyway.

The conspiracies will still be there tomorrow. (This is just where I land. No shame to people who want to find the truth. More power to ya! I’m usually just too sad ❤️)

With love, your friendly neighborhood conspiracy theorist.

Personally, I had to lose some people to find mine. & myself. The loss of friendships was painful, but it made space to discover who I am and what I believe with minimal outside influence.

It created margin & in that margin my relationships deepened to something beyond friendship.

The years I thought would kill me really did make me stronger, but not just stronger. They made me kinder, more understanding, more capable of relationship.

This sounds harsh, but I know I wouldn’t be where I am today if those people had stayed in my life. I know God took them out so He could give me the people I have today. People who not only loved me when I didn’t love myself, but taught me how.

I’ve had Psalm 131:4 memorized since I was a kid. “Set a guard over my mouth, Lord; keep watch over the door of my lips.” You just think I’m unfiltered online, you should seeeee Marco Polo. Constantly I type things out and have to hit backspace & just move on. I said I’m a Christian, not Christ himself, you know? I’m doing my best.

I have a lot of thoughts & about 60% of them will probably hurt your feelings.

This is what has brought purpose to my pain. It’s what closes my ears to the noise of the world. It’s what inspires faith in the face of a Goliath and gives me confidence for the next steps.

“One day, God will use all of this for good” I remind myself. He’ll turn it into hope & then I’ll be able to hand that hope down to my children. Deal it out to others with my story.

We need more hope dealers. People who know what’s happening in the world & face it with a joyful noise. Christians who use their pain to inspire change rather than drag others down.

You can’t hand out hope if you have none for yourself, so maybe start there ❤️
